I agree with you.

44:24.057 --> 44:31.407
I want to, it'd be nice if they'd make me serve my term as community service or something where I could.

44:31.427 --> 44:36.094
Just help them out with it.

44:36.114 --> 44:36.314
Yeah.

44:36.334 --> 44:37.135
I hate having,

44:37.672 --> 44:42.797
sitting around with guys in the Polk County Jail talking about Point's Uncle Tom's cabin.

44:42.817 --> 44:50.385
They'll listen and they'll learn, but there are better places to... That knowledge can be used more productively.

44:50.405 --> 44:50.525
Yeah.

44:51.446 --> 44:55.230
You might... I'm going to shut this up.

44:55.250 --> 44:57.072
...back with the academic community.

44:57.092 --> 44:59.915
This is kind of what I was asking in a roundabout way.

45:00.055 --> 45:04.120
I mean, when I said that this case is really in a class by itself.

45:04.180 --> 45:07.223
But that isn't the major factor to get my...

45:08.806 --> 45:12.650
Standing back in the academic community, that's a selfish motive.

45:12.670 --> 45:14.893
I owe it to them.

45:14.913 --> 45:17.135
At this point, I've screwed up.

45:17.216 --> 45:20.659
I could have collected doorknobs or stuff out of buildings being torn out.

45:20.679 --> 45:25.305
What would you like to say to the academic community?

45:25.365 --> 45:27.067
I'm at a loss for words, really.

45:27.087 --> 45:28.028
I don't know what to say.

45:28.048 --> 45:31.612
I mean, how did you feel yesterday when you saw this process?

45:31.632 --> 45:34.936
Oh, I felt terrible personally for those people.

45:35.396 --> 45:36.197
When I seen it,

45:36.548 --> 45:38.150
From a person to person.

45:38.590 --> 45:41.053
When I looked those people in the face, I was ashamed.

45:41.113 --> 45:42.414
Really?

45:42.434 --> 45:44.276
Did any of them look at you in the eyes?

45:44.937 --> 45:46.299
Did you establish eye contact?

45:46.439 --> 45:48.821
Yeah, some, but most of them were afraid to look at me.

45:48.841 --> 45:51.164
I didn't want to have anybody afraid of me.

45:51.424 --> 45:52.105
How about Magoo?

45:52.766 --> 45:56.069
Oh, I wanted to shake his hand, and he wouldn't.

45:56.089 --> 45:59.233
You might have known the similarities.

46:00.954 --> 46:02.456
He looked a lot like you.

46:02.516 --> 46:03.417
I was amazed.

46:05.067 --> 46:06.048
Go ahead.

46:06.288 --> 46:13.876
The similarities and what the consequences were to him personally, he looked like he'd been agonized, because he'd been bum-wrapped.

46:13.896 --> 46:16.038
I would have never done that to him, you know?

46:16.058 --> 46:17.199
But I didn't deliver any.

46:17.279 --> 46:18.541
I found the damn thing.

46:19.021 --> 46:22.805
Was this more like the military people call a target of opportunity?

46:22.865 --> 46:25.788
I mean, it was just something that presented itself.

46:25.808 --> 46:31.914
Just as I was walking by a public area, it was laying on a counter.

46:32.114 --> 46:32.454
Really?

46:32.635 --> 46:33.015
Yeah.

46:34.396 --> 46:40.824
That did enable you to enter the next level of collectible, didn't it?

46:40.845 --> 46:40.945
Yeah.

46:40.965 --> 46:41.646
Is that right?

46:41.826 --> 46:43.408
Yeah.

46:43.688 --> 47:00.551
And I guess the thing that got me in the best was when I go in and talk to librarians and these restricted things, they would automatically assume I was who I was by the knowledge that I had, you know.

47:00.571 --> 47:01.652
Were you ever turned down?

47:07.927 --> 47:09.349
No, I never was.

47:12.253 --> 47:12.634
Never was.

47:12.694 --> 47:23.589
Were the methods as described by the various witnesses, were they essentially correct ways that you did manage to gain access?

47:23.609 --> 47:27.655
Pretty much, but most of it wasn't a matter of poor security.

47:27.675 --> 47:29.197
It was a matter of opportunity.

47:31.821 --> 47:33.343
Some of it security, but...

47:34.285 --> 47:39.691
I mean, did things go out the windows the way they described it?

47:39.831 --> 47:41.513
Well, I don't know.

47:41.774 --> 47:50.123
I could go through any institution, and if one way wasn't amenable, I could find three or four other ways.

47:53.267 --> 47:53.507
Wow.

47:55.049 --> 47:57.392
And you never get scared while you were doing this?

47:57.412 --> 48:02.858
No, for instance, why don't we keep this off the record?

48:03.277 --> 48:06.580
I'm sorry, you said you're pretty ingenious of resources.

48:06.681 --> 48:08.362
Now, the machine's on.

48:08.422 --> 48:09.804
I'm not going to deceive you.

48:11.506 --> 48:15.930
Well, I'm ingenious with resources, you know.

48:16.291 --> 48:22.097
Tell me about, what were you going to say about that institution, that Ivy League institution?

48:22.117 --> 48:27.302
Well, I may need that as a marketing head in the future.

48:27.482 --> 48:29.925
And I almost have to go there.

48:31.576 --> 48:37.903
One time I almost got killed in a book dump wader crawling up that to get to the... What was this?

48:39.084 --> 48:40.105
Out in California.

48:41.006 --> 48:45.410
Wait, do you remember that?

48:45.430 --> 48:45.891
Well... Okay.

48:45.911 --> 48:46.692
Tell me what happened.

48:46.712 --> 48:55.661
Well, I was crawling up to get to the closed stacks, and they turned the wader on, and I jumped off, and I got caught in that machinery and dragged up and... Really?

48:55.681 --> 48:56.202
...run through that.

48:56.222 --> 48:56.922
I'd have been crushed.

48:56.942 --> 48:57.623
That's not funny.

48:57.763 --> 48:59.525
No.

48:59.545 --> 49:00.486
But, uh...

49:00.955 --> 49:05.161
Such is the passion in the chase, you know, for the rare tone.

49:07.605 --> 49:11.130
I'm sorry to laugh.

49:11.151 --> 49:13.574
Did you ever want to tell people about this?

49:13.594 --> 49:20.044
Oh, yeah, I did.

49:21.458 --> 49:23.261
It's kind of a modern day Indiana Jones.

49:23.301 --> 49:28.127
Maybe someday I can give a lecture at the Roxborough Club or something.

49:28.147 --> 49:31.332
On the book collecting.

49:31.352 --> 49:32.233
The Groyer Club.

49:32.253 --> 49:33.575
The Groyer Club, yeah.

49:33.595 --> 49:34.676
The Groyer Club.

49:34.696 --> 49:40.144
Daniel Fearing had a book exhibit there in 1917 or 1912 or something.

49:40.244 --> 49:41.145
Is that right?

49:41.366 --> 49:46.613
Well, Scheide, I was telling you about it the other day, had an exhibit there last year, which I went to.

49:46.673 --> 49:46.893
Oh, he did?

49:46.913 --> 49:46.993
Oh.

49:47.014 --> 49:48.616
And that's how I met Scheide.

49:48.716 --> 49:48.816
Yeah.

49:49.167 --> 49:52.866
and then he invited me out to his collection of Princeton.

52:39.301 --> 52:43.867
The home of Carl Thrasher.

52:44.367 --> 52:46.310
Who's Carl Thrasher?

52:46.390 --> 52:54.941
Well, Carl was one of my... Carl was the only other individual that I met.

52:54.961 --> 52:57.524
Now, don't tell anybody this.

52:57.564 --> 53:00.668
This guy was abused and was a bee...

53:01.441 --> 53:03.423
Excuse me.

53:03.984 --> 53:05.165
Don't put this in the people.

53:05.186 --> 53:05.706
No, I won't.

53:05.746 --> 53:06.727
They'll pick him up.

53:06.747 --> 53:07.248
Okay.

53:07.348 --> 53:08.890
I don't even have his name.

53:08.910 --> 53:10.031
You met another guy.

53:10.051 --> 53:10.152
Okay.

53:10.712 --> 53:15.398
This young man was the only other book thief I met in my whole career.

53:15.718 --> 53:15.898
Okay.

53:16.159 --> 53:19.222
I moved into Ottumwa, and he got to be friends with me.

53:19.262 --> 53:20.244
He was a teenager.

53:20.264 --> 53:23.027
He was into American history.

53:24.188 --> 53:28.675
And he was as knowledgeable about American Indians as we are about books, believe it or not.

53:28.735 --> 53:35.326
Even though he was kicked out of school and a problem with people, he was really, you know, it was a tragic thing.

53:35.547 --> 53:41.937
But anyhow, he'd been nailing the Ottumwa Public Library for their Indian books.

53:43.179 --> 53:48.508
And here I was trying to hide this collection, and I found out, and I says to Carl, I says,

53:49.231 --> 53:51.393
You've got to quit doing this.

53:51.493 --> 53:55.137
Here, this place had been, you know, I didn't get any books.

53:55.157 --> 53:57.819
If you tell me a public library, you're losing all kinds of books.

53:58.380 --> 53:59.901
And here I am sitting here.

54:00.442 --> 54:04.446
So I befriended him and, uh... Don't forget, I need a roll of film.

54:04.966 --> 54:06.468
Oh, okay.

54:06.488 --> 54:09.351
Any kind of drug store or something.

54:09.371 --> 54:10.352
Any convenience store.

54:11.913 --> 54:12.714
Oh, okay.

54:13.294 --> 54:13.995
I'll take you downtown.

54:14.035 --> 54:19.120
But anyhow, I showed him my book collection and got him interested in

54:19.775 --> 54:20.736
Antiquarian books.

54:20.816 --> 54:25.401
I said, Carl, stop taking books out of the Ottumwa Public Library.

54:25.441 --> 54:28.024
If you ever need books, you tell me what you need.

54:28.044 --> 54:30.027
There are plenty of Antiquarian bookstores.

54:30.547 --> 54:31.729
He didn't want old books.

54:31.769 --> 54:33.130
He just wanted the information.

54:33.150 --> 54:34.552
He said, I'm different than you, Steve.

54:34.572 --> 54:35.653
I just want the information.

54:36.094 --> 54:39.918
I said, there are plenty of stores in Minneapolis you can buy that, not here in Ottumwa.

54:40.218 --> 54:41.820
I'll buy you any book you want.

54:42.341 --> 54:42.601
That's right.

54:42.621 --> 54:45.625
Don't take them out of the Ottumwa Public Library.

54:47.186 --> 54:47.807
Did he stop?

54:48.277 --> 54:49.699
I believe he did, yeah.

54:50.260 --> 54:52.264
But now they're blaming me for those books.

54:53.967 --> 55:01.680
But I don't want to see anything happen to them, and I just feel so bad.

55:02.020 --> 55:10.555
I tried, through the schools, to get, I knew an ex-faculty member at the Otoma High School, to get people interested in

55:11.041 --> 55:13.243
in his knowledge of Indian stuff.

55:13.263 --> 55:21.090
Because if you got the kid talking on Indian stuff and somebody could inspire him, they could get him into his other schoolwork and get him to learn.

55:21.110 --> 55:23.692
Because they were saying, oh, don't hang around with him.

55:23.772 --> 55:28.196
He's a troublemaker and he's a bad boy.

55:28.216 --> 55:29.237
And he was a good kid.

55:29.257 --> 55:30.618
He come from a terrible home.

55:30.678 --> 55:33.701
His dad stole him from his mother when he was eight months old.

55:33.721 --> 55:36.803
And he lived alone with his father.

55:36.823 --> 55:40.086
And his father beat him since he was really young.

55:40.319 --> 55:42.884
He used to come over to my house crying and drunk.

55:42.944 --> 55:46.210
And he was just an emotional wreck from the terrible home life.

55:46.230 --> 55:50.918
And all he had was his books and his Indian thing that he was interested in.

55:51.038 --> 55:56.168
And the way I got in with him is I brought Billy Laquay down, who's an Indian also.

55:56.809 --> 55:59.373
And the two of them got to be friends.

55:59.393 --> 56:04.723
And there aren't very many Native Americans here in Ottumwa.

56:04.855 --> 56:09.903
as much blood as he was, he was almost, you know, three quarters and bellies full.

56:10.344 --> 56:17.455
So through, see, I lived in the Native American part of Minneapolis.

56:17.475 --> 56:18.897
They got a ghetto that's like that.

56:19.599 --> 56:23.264
And through that, I got to be friends with him.

56:23.304 --> 56:26.469
And then we had this book thing in common.

56:26.489 --> 56:31.217
So he was my closest friend in Ottumwa.

56:34.572 --> 56:40.238
Well, I am not interested in that at all, so I wouldn't even worry about it.

56:40.258 --> 56:42.501
Oh, no, no, I just don't want him in trouble, that's all.

56:42.521 --> 56:43.582
Okay, come on.

56:43.602 --> 56:45.885
Look at all these guys.

56:48.728 --> 56:48.848
Yeah.

56:48.868 --> 56:53.634
Do you know of this book thing together here, me and this young fella, you know?

56:53.654 --> 56:55.296
He's the only other book thief I ever met.

56:57.478 --> 57:01.002
Well, he certainly didn't operate at your level.

57:01.640 --> 57:03.963
Oh, no, no, no, it didn't.

57:03.983 --> 57:06.326
Of course you are sophistication.

57:06.346 --> 57:14.335
No.

57:14.355 --> 57:16.237
You know what I told them?

57:16.257 --> 57:19.020
They had the weirdest crime column in this town.

57:19.541 --> 57:26.169
One time I read that an old lady was arrested in the Hy-Vee for stealing cans of tuna fish.

57:26.189 --> 57:27.871
It was in the paper.

57:27.891 --> 57:28.812
Then another time,

57:30.125 --> 57:38.453
A couple of high school girls were arrested for taking sunflower seeds and peanuts down at the drugstore.

57:38.553 --> 57:47.643
And I said, Carl, if I ever get in trouble, they're going to put me right in the October newspaper crime column with the tuna fish thief.

57:47.663 --> 57:50.806
Well, I guess I wound up with that.

57:50.826 --> 57:53.048
Never, Steve.

57:53.088 --> 57:53.669
Don't forget his film.

57:53.789 --> 57:55.150
No, I won't.

57:55.631 --> 57:59.895
I do have a roll, but I think I might want to shoot one of 24 shots.

